# Regression test for FastScape checkpoint/restart of the basement and silt
# fraction fields. A model with a marine component is run to the End time in
# one go (writing checkpoints along the way), then resumed from the last
# checkpoint and continued to the same End time. Because FastScape runs
# deterministically on the root process, a correct restart must reproduce the
# uninterrupted run bit-for-bit.
#
# This exercises the bug where FastScape<dim>::save() snapshotted the basement
# and silt fraction arrays with the surface-elevation accessor
# (fastscape_copy_h_) instead of fastscape_copy_basement_ / fastscape_copy_f_.
# With that bug the restarted sediment thickness (elevation - basement)
# collapses to ~0, so the resumed run diverges from the straight run. The stock
# fastscape tests use identical bedrock and sediment erosion parameters and can
# never see this; here the sediment is deliberately far more incisive and
# diffusive than the bedrock so the corruption is observable in the topography.
#
# To exercise the silt-fraction half of the restart (not just the basement),
# two things are set up. First, the sea level is raised (the base model only
# floods a thin strip) so a substantial part of the domain is marine and the
# silt fraction is actually used. Second, the silt and sand marine transport
# coefficients are made distinct, which
# lets the silt fraction evolve away from its reference value and feed back on
# the topography. Silt is set larger than sand (finer material travels farther),
# which is also the ordering for which the marine diffusion stays convergent at
# this basin depth. With basement restored correctly but the silt fraction
# still taken from the surface elevation, this configuration diverges by tens
# of metres offshore, so the test guards the silt-fraction save independently
# of the basement save.
#
# Enable if: ASPECT_WITH_FASTSCAPE

include $ASPECT_SOURCE_DIR/tests/fastscape_test_fixed_ghost_nodes.prm

set End time           = 1.2e5
set Resume computation = false

subsection Checkpointing
  set Steps between checkpoint = 1
  set Resume checkpoint = 2
end

subsection Mesh deformation
  subsection Fastscape
    subsection Erosional parameters
      set Bedrock river incision rate  = 1e-5
      set Sediment river incision rate = 2e-4
      set Bedrock diffusivity          = 1e-2
      set Sediment diffusivity         = 5e-1
    end

    # Raise the sea level so a substantial part of the domain is marine, and
    # give silt and sand distinct transport coefficients (silt > sand) so the
    # marine silt fraction evolves away from its reference value. Together these exercise the silt-fraction part of
    # the checkpoint/restart.
    set Use marine component = true
    subsection Marine parameters
      set Sea level                  = 0
      set Silt transport coefficient = 5e2
      set Sand transport coefficient = 5e1
    end
  end
end

subsection Postprocess
  subsection Topography
    set Time between text output = 1.2e5
    set Output to file           = true
  end
end
